    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "Hi!\r\n\r\nFollowing this issue, I have been using [these changes](https://github.com/arnaud-lb/grpc/pull/1/files) successfully for months.\r\n\r\nIf there is an agreement on the feature and the general way it's implemented, I would like to work on a pull request.\r\n\r\nI will try to describe the changes:\r\n\r\nA new parameter named `async` is added to the `Call` class constructor in the PHP extension. When it's set to true, `Call::startBatch` is asynchronous: batches are queued on a separate `grpc_completion_queue` and no attempt is made to immediately pluck/drain the queue. Because of this, the data related to batches outlives the `Call::startBatch` calls, and must be stored on the heap, in a new `batch` struct. Batch initialisation and housekeeping code has been moved to batch.c.\r\n\r\nThe user must call `Call::drainCompletionQueue` regularly until it returns 0, which indicates that there is nothing to drain anymore. The nodejs extension does something similar automatically at the beginning of the event loop. In PHP, the user-land event loop implementations have to handle this. In my case, I drain the queue by using a react-php timer.\r\n\r\nIn the PHP library, the `UnaryCall::callAsync` method is added. It takes a callback, that is called when the unary call completes.\r\n\r\nThere is some work I still have to do:\r\n\r\n - Rebasing to master\r\n - Generating async-capable grpc/protobuf stubs\r\n\r\nWhat do you think ?"
  },
